      Loews / Boardwalk Pipeline
   =20
 =20
The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission regulates the maximum rates that n=
atural gas pipelines can charge to customers. The rate regulation essential=
ly allows the pipeline company to recover its =E2=80=9Ccost of service,=E2=
=80=9D that is, its operating costs plus a reasonable=C2=A0return on its in=
vested capital. In 2005, FERC decided that pipelines organized as partnersh=
ips, which do not pay corporate taxes, could act=C2=A0as though=C2=A0they h=
ad to pay corporate taxes in calculating their costs.[1]=C2=A0This allowed =
partnership pipelines to charge higher rates than they otherwise would, and=
 led to a boom of publicly traded=C2=A0pipeline partnerships, often called =
=E2=80=9Cmaster limited partnerships=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CMLPs.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Loews Corp., a big conglomerate, formed an MLP called Boardwalk Pipeline=
 Partners LP, put some pipeline assets into Boardwalk, and took it public i=
n 2005. Because the FERC rules were new and controversial at the time, it i=
ncluded a provision in the Boardwalk partnership agreement that allowed Loe=
ws to take it private again if the rules changed. The idea was that if the =
FERC rules changed such that MLPs could no longer include hypothetical taxe=
s in their rate calculations, then it would be bad for Boardwalk to be a pu=
blic partnership, and so=C2=A0Loews would be able to force all the Boardwal=
k shareholders=C2=A0(technically, unitholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0holders of lim=
ited partnership interests) to sell their shares=C2=A0and take it private. =
(Then it would be a corporate pipeline and get to charge for taxes again.) =
This =E2=80=9Ccall right=E2=80=9D was written to say that if Boardwalk got =
an opinion of counsel saying that Boardwalk=E2=80=99s status as an MLP =E2=
=80=9Chas or will reasonably likely in the future have a material adverse e=
ffect on the maximum applicable rate that can be charged to customers,=E2=
=80=9D then Loews can buy back all the Boardwalk shares at a price equal to=
 the average closing prices over the six months before it exercises the cal=
l.=C2=A0In March 2018, responding to a court decision, FERC announced a new=
 policy that MLPs will not generally be able to include hypothetical taxes =
in calculating their rates, exactly the thing Loews had worried about in 20=
05. In the actual world of 2018, though, this news was not particularly bad=
 for Boardwalk. A lot of its revenues come from negotiated rates that are n=
ot really affected by FERC maximum rates. Also the FERC rate-setting proces=
s is complicated; Boardwalk could keep charging its old rates until someone=
 filed a =E2=80=9Crate case=E2=80=9D asking it to change, and the rate case=
 is a long multi-factor regulatory determination, not just =E2=80=9Creduce =
your rates by 20% because you don=E2=80=99t pay taxes=E2=80=9D or whatever.=
=C2=A0Also the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017, which reduced federal corpora=
te income taxes, reduced the advantages of being an MLP: MLPs don=E2=80=99t=
 pay corporate taxes, but corporate taxes aren=E2=80=99t as high as they us=
ed to be. Also the tax accounting for FERC rates is complicated, and the wa=
y that FERC crafted the transition from the old regime to the new one =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0specifically how it treated deferred tax liabilities =E2=80=94 =
might actually be=C2=A0good=C2=A0for MLPs=E2=80=99 rate calculations.[2]So =
in March 2018, when FERC announced that MLPs would no longer be able to cha=
rge for hypothetical taxes, Loews and Boardwalk did not panic. They analyze=
d the potential impact of the changes and decided that they would be manage=
able; the worst case was a negative impact of about $20.5 million, but it c=
ould be much better depending on the specific rules that FERC used to trans=
ition the deferred tax liabilities.[3]=C2=A0But there was that call right. =
And Boardwalk and Loews got to thinking about it. Boardwalk=E2=80=99s share=
s were trading at historically=C2=A0low prices, and arguably the reason for=
 that was a classic =E2=80=9Cpublic markets are too short-term-focused=E2=
=80=9D reason. MLPs are generally income investments; people buy them becau=
se they pay high dividends. Boardwalk cut its dividend in 2014 to reinvest =
more in growth[4]:In 2014, Boardwalk stunned investors by cutting its quart=
erly distribution from $0.5325 to $0.10 per unit, making Boardwalk one of t=
he lowest yielding MLPs in the industry. Boardwalk=E2=80=99s trading price =
fell from the low $30s to the low $10s almost overnight. The unit price nev=
er again approached its former levels.=C2=A0Between 2014 and 2017, Boardwal=
k spent $2.077 billion on capital expenditures, including $1.6 billion in g=
rowth capital expenditures. During the same period, Boardwalk distributed $=
405.1 million to unitholders. There is evidence=C2=A0that investors were un=
sure about how to value the growth capital expenditures.The idea is of cour=
se that you cut the dividend, invest the money in growth, grow, and then ev=
entually pay a much higher dividend. But Boardwalk was in the middle of tha=
t process. The present value of its future dividends had gone up because of=
 its investments in growth, but its current dividends had not. And the publ=
ic MLP market, a niche market that really cares about current yield, did no=
t give it credit for that growth.So if Loews could exercise the call right,=
 it could buy back all the shares of Boardwalk cheaply and then own all tha=
t upside itself. It estimated internally that there was =E2=80=9C$1.557 bil=
lion in =E2=80=98Value Creation=E2=80=99 that=E2=80=9D it could get by exer=
cising the call right. There was no real advantage anymore to keeping the p=
ipeline assets in an MLP =E2=80=94=C2=A0the favorable tax treatment was goi=
ng away, and corporate taxes were lower anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0and there was=
 an advantage to buying them back cheap. So Boardwalk and Loews executives =
asked: Can we exercise the call right?Oversimplifying, the question there i=
s, did Loews have the right to call Boardwalk=E2=80=99s shares=C2=A0if FERC=
=E2=80=99s tax treatment changed in the way it worried about in 2005, or di=
d Loews have that right only if the tax treatment changed=C2=A0and it was b=
ad for Boardwalk? Because the exact thing Loews had worried about in 2005 =
=E2=80=94 FERC rule changes that would prevent MLPs from charging customers=
 for taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0had occurred. But it turned out to be fine. But L=
oews wanted to exercise the call right anyway, because that would be profit=
able.So it went out to its lawyers and asked them to give it an opinion say=
ing that FERC=E2=80=99s rules were changing in a way that =E2=80=9Chas or w=
ill reasonably likely in the future have a material adverse effect on the m=
aximum applicable rate that can be charged to customers,=E2=80=9D as requir=
ed by the partnership agreement.=C2=A0This was a tricky opinion to give. Th=
e new FERC rules weren=E2=80=99t final, for one thing, and it wasn=E2=80=99=
t clear what the final rules would say. Also they=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0have a material adverse effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0revenue, on t=
he actual rates it actually charged customers. But they=C2=A0might=C2=A0hav=
e a negative effect on the =E2=80=9Cmaximum applicable rate,=E2=80=9D or wh=
at is more technically called the =E2=80=9Crecourse rate,=E2=80=9D the FERC=
-set rate that customers would pay if they didn=E2=80=99t come to a differe=
nt agreement. They would only have this effect if customers filed a rate ca=
se, and there=E2=80=99d be a lot of other factors to consider in any rate c=
ase, and blah blah blah, but in some oversimplified sense if you could char=
ge customers for taxes before and now you can=E2=80=99t, sure, the regulato=
ry rates you can charge them will go down in some straightforward arithmeti=
c sense.[5]So that=E2=80=99s what Boardwalk=E2=80=99s lawyers at Baker Bott=
s LLP considered: They ignored all the messy economic realities and focused=
 on the simple arithmetic of not charging for taxes anymore.The Baker Botts=
 team clarified that their rate expert had not analyzed the Revised Policy=
=E2=80=99s effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s rates. Instead, the analysis consi=
dered =E2=80=9CHypothetical Rates.=E2=80=9D Notes taken by a Baker Botts pa=
rtner reveal that everyone focused on the core issue: There would be =E2=80=
=9Cno actual change=E2=80=94no effect yet screw min[ority].=E2=80=9D That w=
as obviously a =E2=80=9Cchallenging fact.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Of course I am, her=
e and elsewhere, quoting from a court decision=C2=A0in a lawsuit against Bo=
ardwalk. Helpfully the decision includes a picture of those notes:The new F=
ERC rules would have no actual effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s business, but =
they would affect the =E2=80=9Chypothetical rates=E2=80=9D it could charge,=
 which would (arguably) allow it to exercise the call right and buy all the=
 shares back cheaply, which would =E2=80=9Cscrew min,=E2=80=9D which is a =
=E2=80=9Cchallenging fact.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a good summary of the situ=
ation! Not the sort of note you want to turn over in litigation, but a good=
 summary nonetheless.The lawyers got more or less comfortable issuing the o=
pinion, and at the end of April 2018 Loews and Boardwalk started to signal =
that they would exercise the call right. The market reaction was bad:Subjec=
ted to the overhang of the pricing formula, Boardwalk=E2=80=99s trading pri=
ce declined steadily. The units closed at $10.94 on May 1, then at $10.88 o=
n May 2. On May 3, the price fell to $10.01. On May 4, it fell to $9.56. On=
 May 7, the units closed at $9.26. =E2=80=A6As investors began to understan=
d the effect of the Call Right, they became outraged.But a bad market react=
ion was good for Loews.=C2=A0In May 6, 2018, Deutsche Bank AG research put =
out a note about =E2=80=9Cthe =E2=80=98Prisoner's Dilemma=E2=80=99 that Loe=
ws had created=E2=80=9D[6]:Stakeholders could expect no higher price for sh=
ares of BWP than $11.50 unless Loews chose voluntarily to tender at a highe=
r share price (or chose not exercise at all). Given that the probable =E2=
=80=9Cbest=E2=80=9D the stakeholders could do seemed to be around $11.50 in=
 August 2017, there seemed to be little incentive to hold onto BWP shares a=
bove that price. And so the stock has=C2=A0begun to fall. However, as the s=
tock falls, so too does the 180-average price for which Loews can demand te=
nder. This has engendered a real-time game theory practice known as =E2=80=
=9Cthe prisoner=E2=80=99s dilemma.=E2=80=9D By this logic, the stakeholders=
 assume the worst of their fellow stakeholders and aim to sell first in ord=
er to arguably . . . get a better price than those who wait. This has creat=
ed a pile-on where stakeholders are willing to part with their shares below=
 what some might argue is fair value. And no shareholder has the incentive =
to pay more than this price if Loews has the option to tender below that pr=
ice level.Boardwalk=E2=80=99s shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0including a hedge=
 fund, Bandera Partners LLC =E2=80=94=C2=A0started complaining (1) that Loe=
ws should not be able to exercise the call right and (2) that in any case i=
t was manipulating the stock price by=C2=A0talking about exercising the cal=
l right, pushing the stock price down so that when it eventually exercised =
the call right it could pay a lower price.=C2=A0But Loews did it anyway. It=
 got the opinion, exercised the call right and paid $12.06 per share; the a=
cquisition closed on July 18, 2018. =E2=80=9CHours after the closing,=E2=80=
=9D FERC issued a final rule on the treatment of taxes for MLPs that was ge=
nerally very favorable to MLPs, including particularly on the transition fo=
r deferred tax liabilities (=E2=80=9CADIT=E2=80=9D):FERC reiterated that it=
s policy would not=C2=A0automatically permit MLP pipelines to recover an in=
come tax allowance in their cost of service, but MLPs would not be preclude=
d from arguing in a rate case that they were entitled to an income tax allo=
wance based on an evidentiary record.Critically, FERC stated that MLPs that=
