When I was an investment banker I made some clever visualization of somethi=
ng or other, and was pleased with it, and showed it to a more senior banker=
, and she was like =E2=80=9Cwell this is good but you have to change the co=
lors, you can=E2=80=99t have red in a presentation.=E2=80=9D I was a bit ta=
ken aback. She said =E2=80=9Csee, red is the color of losses, you cannot sh=
ow a client anything red, it will make them think of losing money.=E2=80=9D=
 I still did not quite believe her? Sure yes of course if you give someone =
a table of dollar values you will want them to be in black, and if you prin=
t them in red for flair the client will think they are negative and be anno=
yed, but it cannot really be the case that any use of literal red ink in a =
presentation will subliminally remind clients of figurative red ink and mak=
e them not want to hire you? Or that=E2=80=99s what I thought when=C2=A0I w=
as young and naive.Anyway here=E2=80=99s a behavioral-finance paper:We use =
a novel online experiment to investigate the impact of emotional imagery on=
 investment behavior. Participants are exposed to a nature-related and a no=
n-nature set of images with varying degrees of valence during several inves=
tment decisions. We demonstrate that positive imagery significantly increas=
es and negative imagery significantly decreases investment, despite the fac=
t that the imagery does not provide additional information relevant to the =
investment tasks and should be disregarded by rational investors. We furthe=
r show that exposure to nature-related imagery results in significantly hig=
her investment compared to non-nature imagery. Our findings provide importa=
nt insights for regulators, investors, and the investment industry and esta=
blish the basis for further research.That=E2=80=99s the abstract to =E2=80=
=9CPositivity and Nature: How Images Increase Investment,=E2=80=9D by Koen =
van Boxel, Philipp Decke, Sven Nolte and Judith Schneider. The investments =
were hypothetical, not real money. Still, sure, why not. It is the case tha=
t a lot of hedge funds are  named for geological features=C2=A0of the New E=
ngland coastline. Make the clients close their eyes and think about=C2=A0sa=
iling in the Nantucket Sound and then, bam, ask them for money. I get it.Co=
unterpoint: There is a huge investment boom going on in extremely unnatural=
 digital images of=C2=A0apes and punks and stuff? I suppose someone should =
do a series of non-fungible tokens that are digitally generated images of s=
oothing landscapes, see if those do even better.
