to Money Stuff and other great Bloomberg newsletters here. Thanks![1] The t=
heory is that a partnership is a pass-through entity: It doesn=E2=80=99t pa=
y taxes on income, but its income is attributed to its partners, who do (ge=
nerally) pay taxes. So a pipeline partnership that is owned by some corpora=
tions *does* have a tax expense; it=E2=80=99s just that the partners pay th=
e taxes, not the partnership.[2] From last Friday=E2=80=99s Delaware Chance=
ry Court opinion=C2=A0in Bandera Master Fund LP v. Boardwalk Pipeline Partn=
ers LP (citations omitted):=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA related component of a pipeline=
=E2=80=99s cost of service is ADIT [accumulated deferred income taxes], whi=
ch is an accounting concept that arises because various tax provisions auth=
orize pipelines to depreciate their assets on an accelerated basis. When ca=
lculating recourse rates, however, FERC uses straight-line depreciation. Be=
cause a pipeline can claim depreciation more quickly for tax purposes than =
for rate setting, the pipeline pays lower income taxes in the years when ac=
celerated depreciation applies, resulting in greater cash flows than FERC=
=E2=80=99s rate-setting calculations contemplate. Once the period of accele=
rated depreciation ends, the process reverses, and the pipeline ends up pay=
ing higher taxes than FERC=E2=80=99s rate-setting calculations contemplate.=
 By accelerating depreciation and deferring taxes, the pipeline benefits fr=
om the time-value of money. To reflect the fact that the taxes ultimately m=
ust be paid, the pipeline records the accumulated value of the tax deferral=
 on its balance sheet as ADIT. During the years when the pipeline benefits =
from accelerated depreciation and pays lower taxes, the=C2=A0ADIT balance b=
uilds up. After the period of accelerated depreciation, once the pipeline b=
egins paying higher taxes, the ADIT balance declines. In substance, the acc=
elerated depreciation acts as an interest-free loan from the government tha=
t the pipeline eventually must repay. The balance on the pipeline=E2=80=99s=
 balance sheet is therefore referred to as an =E2=80=98ADIT liability.=E2=
=80=99 More importantly for present purposes, FERC historically treated a p=
ositive ADIT balance as a cost-free source of capital. FERC therefore subtr=
acted the ADIT balance from the pipeline=E2=80=99s rate base for purposes o=
f the cost-of-service calculation.=E2=80=9D The question, after FERC=E2=80=
=99s March 2018 announcement of its new policy, was how old ADIT balances w=
ould be treated. The good case for MLPs would be if the ADIT balances just =
went to zero: no taxes, so no deferred tax liability. This would give MLPs =
more room to charge high rates (because they=E2=80=99d no longer have imput=
ed zero-cost financing). The bad case would be if the MLPs had to, e.g., re=
fund ADIT back to ratepayers. The actual result, FERC announced in July, wa=
s the good one for MLPs: ADIT balances would go to zero.=C2=A0[3]=C2=A0The =
chief executive officer of Boardwalk, Stanley Horton, =E2=80=9Cinstructed B=
en Johnson, Boardwalk=E2=80=99s Vice President of Rates and Tariffs, to con=
duct an expedited analysis of the possible impact on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s th=
ree interstate pipelines.=E2=80=9D[3] He did, and the impact was mild: Two =
were =E2=80=9Crelatively protected=E2=80=9D from any impact, because most o=
f their =E2=80=9Cvolumes were subject to negotiated rates, meaning that a c=
hange in cost-of-service-based rates would not affect the pipeline.=E2=80=
=9D The third =E2=80=9Chad potential exposure to a rate case, but it too ha=
d factors that would help in defending against any challenge to its rates. =
Among other things, Texas Gas served highly competitive markets, and a majo=
rity of its contracts with shippers provided for negotiated or discounted r=
ates. Assuming a rate case was filed, Johnson estimated that the downside i=
mpact of eliminating the income tax allowance would be about $20.5 million.=
 Importantly, Johnson characterized his estimate of the downside as a floor=
, because it =E2=80=98ignores any bounce from rate base increase associated=
 with removal of ADIT.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D (See note 2 for ADIT.)=C2=A0[4]=C2=
=A0This and other unattributed quotes in this section are from the Chancery=
 Court opinion, with citations omitted.=C2=A0The links here are generally t=
o the opinion on the Chancery Court website, but here is a copy of the PDF =
archived at Bloomberg, just in case.[5] At one point the opinion quotes Boa=
rdwalk=E2=80=99s general counsel, Michael McMahon, making fun of a FERC off=
icial for doing this sort of oversimplification: =E2=80=9CDuring a discussi=
on of the March 15 FERC Actions, Jonathon Taylor from the FERC Office of Ge=
neral Counsel ... explained that =E2=80=98when a tax expense decreases, so =
does the cost of service.=E2=80=99 At the time, McMahon and his outside cou=
nsel ridiculed that line of reasoning. McMahon wrote to Gregory Junge, a re=
gulatory lawyer: =E2=80=98That was a priceless statement[.] [T]axes go down=
[.] COS goes down[.] This is going to be a train wreck.=E2=80=99 Junge resp=
onded: =E2=80=98That is . . . just [the] type of 1:1 thinking that we were =
trying to explain is not the case.=E2=80=99 And in its comments to FERC on =
the NOPR, Boardwalk rejected that simplistic approach. Boardwalk asserted t=
hat it was =E2=80=98misleading=E2=80=99 to equate a change in the cost of s=
ervice stemming from the removal of the income tax allowance with a =E2=80=
=98rate reduction,=E2=80=99 because a cost-of-service change has =E2=80=98l=
ittle bearing=E2=80=99 on whether or not a rate reduction will occur.=E2=80=
=9D[6]=C2=A0Meanwhile, Barclays Plc put out a research report saying that L=
oews =E2=80=9Cwas using a =E2=80=98loophole=E2=80=99=C2=A0in the Partnershi=
p Agreement =E2=80=98to buy in the assets for what we believe is an extreme=
ly attractive price.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Loews had asked Barclays investment =
bankers for advice on exercising the call right, but Barclays equity resear=
ch and investment banking were =E2=80=94=C2=A0as they=E2=80=99re supposed t=
o be! =E2=80=94=C2=A0managed separately, and the research analysts criticiz=
ed Loews for doing what its bankers were advising on. Loews got mad: =E2=80=
=9CLoews=E2=80=99 management did not like the report, particularly since Lo=
ews had used Barclays for advice on the Call Right. Siegel contacted Gary P=
osternack, Head of Global M&A at Barclays, to express his =E2=80=98dissatis=
faction=E2=80=99 with the report. Posternack emailed Jes Staley, Barclay=E2=
=80=99s then-CEO, with a heads up that he might be =E2=80=98getting a call =
in the next day from Jim Tisch at Loews, who is very upset about some equit=
y research commentary that our analyst put out. I should brief you before y=
ou speak.=E2=80=99 The call ultimately did not take place.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It=
=E2=80=99s a good little story about investment-bank management. In the old=
en days, research analysts pumped up stocks in order to win investment bank=
ing business; under modern rules, research analysts mostly=C2=A0*lose*=C2=
=A0investment banking business by writing mean things about the companies t=
he bankers are pitching.=C2=A0[7] The procedural history is actually more c=
omplicated and interesting than that. What happened is that some other shar=
eholders sued to block the call even before Loews exercised it. That case w=
as dismissed as not yet ripe, and then the plaintiffs reached a settlement =
with Loews and Boardwalk that would allow them to exercise the call but req=
uire them to do it by a certain date, i.e. before the price fell too far. T=
his was done as a class-action settlement that would give Loews a global re=
lease from claims about the call right; the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers tol=
d Loews=E2=80=99 lawyers,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CYour clients want to make this purc=
hase. Getting a release on a deal they want to make anyway is actually an a=
mazing outcome for them.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But when they went to the court to a=
pprove the settlement (after the call right was exercised), Bandera objecte=
d, essentially arguing that the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers had sold out th=
e class=E2=80=99s very good claim in exchange for a fee. The court agreed,=
=C2=A0rejected the settlement and let Bandera take over the class action in=
stead.[8] One side note here. The opinion was not =E2=80=9Cin good faith,=
=E2=80=9D Vice Chancellor Laster concluded, but there's something else weir=
d about it. Boardwalk is a limited partnership organized under Delaware law=
, and the question of whether the new FERC rules would have a =E2=80=9Cmate=
rial adverse effect=E2=80=9D under the partnership agreement is a subtle qu=
estion of Delaware limited partnership law. But the lawyers at Baker Botts =
who wrote the opinion were not Delaware lawyers. This is actually *common*:=
 Most big U.S. companies are incorporated in Delaware, virtually all legal =
issues in U.S. mergers and acquisitions are issues of Delaware law, and mos=
t of the lawyers who advise on those issues are not Delaware lawyers. It=E2=
=80=99s weird! Laster writes: =E2=80=9CA non-Delaware law firm thus rendere=
d a non-explained opinion on the existence of a material adverse effect, a =
subject on which both a Delaware law firm (Richards Layton) and a national =
law firm with a Delaware office (Skadden) would not opine.=E2=80=9D And: =
=E2=80=9CBaker Botts is a sophisticated law firm, but it is not a Delaware =
law firm. Baker=C2=A0Botts is also a leader in transactions involving MLPs,=
 but it is not in the habit of opining on complex issues of Delaware limite=
d partnership law. Many sophisticated firms render closing opinions on rout=
ine issues of Delaware entity law, such as the due formation of an entity o=
r the due authorization of a contract. Baker Botts generally rendered enfor=
ceability opinions under the Delaware Revised Uniform Limited Partnership A=
ct, but the firm did not render opinions more broadly on other Delaware iss=
ues.=C2=A0In this case, Baker Botts took on one of the most difficult issue=
s under Delaware law: determining the existence of a material adverse effec=
t. Neither of the Delaware firms in this case would render such an opinion.=
=E2=80=9D Back when I was a lawyer, licensed and practicing in New York but=
 thinking mainly about Delaware law, I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0found that =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0worrying?=C2=A0
