<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Loews / Boardwalk Pipeline</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Federal Energy Regulatory Commissi=
on regulates the maximum rates that natural gas pipelines can charge to cus=
tomers. The rate regulation essentially allows the pipeline company to reco=
ver its =E2=80=9Ccost of service,=E2=80=9D that is, its operating costs plu=
s a reasonable=C2=A0return on its invested capital. In 2005, FERC decided t=
hat pipelines organized as partnerships, which do not pay corporate taxes, =
could act=C2=A0<em>as though=C2=A0</em>they had to pay corporate taxes in c=
alculating their costs.[1]=C2=A0This allowed partnership pipelines to charg=
e higher rates than they otherwise would, and led to a boom of publicly tra=
ded=C2=A0pipeline partnerships, often called =E2=80=9Cmaster limited partne=
rships=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CMLPs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Loews Corp., a big conglomerate, formed an MLP called Boardwalk Pipel=
ine Partners LP, put some pipeline assets into Boardwalk, and took it publi=
c in 2005. Because the FERC rules were new and controversial at the time, i=
t included a provision in the Boardwalk partnership agreement that allowed =
Loews to take it private again if the rules changed. The idea was that if t=
he FERC rules changed such that MLPs could no longer include hypothetical t=
axes in their rate calculations, then it would be bad for Boardwalk to be a=
 public partnership, and so=C2=A0Loews would be able to force all the Board=
walk shareholders=C2=A0(technically, unitholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0holders of =
limited partnership interests) to sell their shares=C2=A0and take it privat=
e. (Then it would be a corporate pipeline and get to charge for taxes again=
.) This =E2=80=9Ccall right=E2=80=9D was written to say that if Boardwalk g=
ot an opinion of counsel saying that Boardwalk=E2=80=99s status as an MLP =
=E2=80=9Chas or will reasonably likely in the future have a material advers=
e effect on the maximum applicable rate that can be charged to customers,=
=E2=80=9D then Loews can buy back all the Boardwalk shares at a price equal=
 to the average closing prices over the six months before it exercises the =
call.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In March 2018, responding to a =
court decision, FERC announced a new policy that MLPs will not generally be=
 able to include hypothetical taxes in calculating their rates, exactly the=
 thing Loews had worried about in 2005. In the actual world of 2018, though=
, this news was not particularly bad for Boardwalk. A lot of its revenues c=
ome from negotiated rates that are not really affected by FERC maximum rate=
s. Also the FERC rate-setting process is complicated; Boardwalk could keep =
charging its old rates until someone filed a =E2=80=9Crate case=E2=80=9D as=
king it to change, and the rate case is a long multi-factor regulatory dete=
rmination, not just =E2=80=9Creduce your rates by 20% because you don=E2=80=
=99t pay taxes=E2=80=9D or whatever.=C2=A0Also the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of=
 2017, which reduced federal corporate income taxes, reduced the advantages=
 of being an MLP: MLPs don=E2=80=99t pay corporate taxes, but corporate tax=
es aren=E2=80=99t as high as they used to be. Also the tax accounting for F=
ERC rates is complicated, and the way that FERC crafted the transition from=
 the old regime to the new one =E2=80=94=C2=A0specifically how it treated d=
eferred tax liabilities =E2=80=94 might actually be=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em=
>for MLPs=E2=80=99 rate calculations.[2]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So=
 in March 2018, when FERC announced that MLPs would no longer be able to ch=
arge for hypothetical taxes, Loews and Boardwalk did not panic. They analyz=
ed the potential impact of the changes and decided that they would be manag=
eable; the worst case was a negative impact of about $20.5 million, but it =
could be much better depending on the specific rules that FERC used to tran=
sition the deferred tax liabilities.[3]=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But there was that call right. And Boardwalk and Loews got to thinking a=
bout it. Boardwalk=E2=80=99s shares were trading at historically=C2=A0low p=
rices, and arguably the reason for that was a classic =E2=80=9Cpublic marke=
ts are too short-term-focused=E2=80=9D reason. MLPs are generally income in=
vestments; people buy them because they pay high dividends. Boardwalk cut i=
ts dividend in 2014 to reinvest more in growth[4]:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2014, Boardwalk stunned investors by cutting its qu=
arterly distribution from $0.5325 to $0.10 per unit, making Boardwalk one o=
f the lowest yielding MLPs in the industry. Boardwalk=E2=80=99s trading pri=
ce fell from the low $30s to the low $10s almost overnight. The unit price =
never again approached its former levels.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Between 2014 and 2017, Boardwalk spent $2.077 billion on capital expen=
ditures, including $1.6 billion in growth capital expenditures. During the =
same period, Boardwalk distributed $405.1 million to unitholders. There is =
evidence=C2=A0that investors were unsure about how to value the growth capi=
tal expenditures.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The idea is =
of course that you cut the dividend, invest the money in growth, grow, and =
then eventually pay a much higher dividend. But Boardwalk was in the middle=
 of that process. The present value of its future dividends had gone up bec=
ause of its investments in growth, but its current dividends had not. And t=
he public MLP market, a niche market that really cares about current yield,=
 did not give it credit for that growth.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So=
 if Loews could exercise the call right, it could buy back all the shares o=
f Boardwalk cheaply and then own all that upside itself. It estimated inter=
nally that there was =E2=80=9C$1.557 billion in =E2=80=98Value Creation=E2=
=80=99 that=E2=80=9D it could get by exercising the call right. There was n=
o real advantage anymore to keeping the pipeline assets in an MLP =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the favorable tax treatment was going away, and corporate taxes were =
lower anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0and there was an advantage to buying them back =
cheap. So Boardwalk and Loews executives asked: Can we exercise the call ri=
ght?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oversimplifying, the question there is=
, did Loews have the right to call Boardwalk=E2=80=99s shares=C2=A0<em>if F=
ERC=E2=80=99s tax treatment changed in the way it worried about in 2005</em=
>, or did Loews have that right only if the tax treatment changed=C2=A0<em>=
and it was bad for Boardwalk? </em>Because the exact thing Loews had worrie=
d about in 2005 =E2=80=94 FERC rule changes that would prevent MLPs from ch=
arging customers for taxes =E2=80=94=C2=A0had occurred. But it turned out t=
o be fine. But Loews wanted to exercise the call right anyway, because that=
 would be profitable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So it went out to its=
 lawyers and asked them to give it an opinion saying that FERC=E2=80=99s ru=
les were changing in a way that =E2=80=9Chas or will reasonably likely in t=
he future have a material adverse effect on the maximum applicable rate tha=
t can be charged to customers,=E2=80=9D as required by the partnership agre=
ement.=C2=A0This was a tricky opinion to give. The new FERC rules weren=E2=
=80=99t final, for one thing, and it wasn=E2=80=99t clear what the final ru=
les would say. Also they=C2=A0<em>wouldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>have a materia=
l adverse effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>revenue</em>, on the actua=
l rates it actually charged customers. But they=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>ha=
ve a negative effect on the =E2=80=9Cmaximum applicable rate,=E2=80=9D or w=
hat is more technically called the =E2=80=9Crecourse rate,=E2=80=9D the FER=
C-set rate that customers would pay if they didn=E2=80=99t come to a differ=
ent agreement. They would only have this effect if customers filed a rate c=
ase, and there=E2=80=99d be a lot of other factors to consider in any rate =
case, and blah blah blah, but in some oversimplified sense if you could cha=
rge customers for taxes before and now you can=E2=80=99t, sure, the regulat=
ory rates you can charge them will go down in some straightforward arithmet=
ic sense.[5]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So that=E2=80=99s what Boardwa=
lk=E2=80=99s lawyers at Baker Botts LLP considered: They ignored all the me=
ssy economic realities and focused on the simple arithmetic of not charging=
 for taxes anymore.</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Baker B=
otts team clarified that their rate expert had not analyzed the Revised Pol=
icy=E2=80=99s effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s rates. Instead, the analysis co=
nsidered =E2=80=9CHypothetical Rates.=E2=80=9D Notes taken by a Baker Botts=
 partner reveal that everyone focused on the core issue: There would be =E2=
=80=9Cno actual change=E2=80=94no effect yet screw min[ority].=E2=80=9D Tha=
t was obviously a =E2=80=9Cchallenging fact.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course I am, here and elsewhere, quoting f=
rom <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.26865=
6/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9M=
