<![endif]--><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The new FERC rules would have no a=
ctual effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s business, but they would affect the =E2=
=80=9Chypothetical rates=E2=80=9D it could charge, which would (arguably) a=
llow it to exercise the call right and buy all the shares back cheaply, whi=
ch would =E2=80=9Cscrew min,=E2=80=9D which is a =E2=80=9Cchallenging fact.=
=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a good summary of the situation! Not the sort of not=
e you want to turn over in litigation, but a good summary nonetheless.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The lawyers got more or less comfortable issuin=
g the opinion, and at the end of April 2018 Loews and Boardwalk started to =
signal that they would exercise the call right. The market reaction was bad=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Subjected to the overhang of =
the pricing formula, Boardwalk=E2=80=99s trading price declined steadily. T=
he units closed at $10.94 on May 1, then at $10.88 on May 2. On May 3, the =
price fell to $10.01. On May 4, it fell to $9.56. On May 7, the units close=
d at $9.26. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As investors began to=
 understand the effect of the Call Right, they became outraged.</p></blockq=
uote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a bad market reaction was <em>good </=
em>for Loews.=C2=A0In May 6, 2018, Deutsche Bank AG research put out a note=
 about =E2=80=9Cthe =E2=80=98Prisoner's Dilemma=E2=80=99 that Loews had cre=
ated=E2=80=9D[6]:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stakeholders =
could expect no higher price for shares of BWP than $11.50 unless Loews cho=
se voluntarily to tender at a higher share price (or chose not exercise at =
all). Given that the probable =E2=80=9Cbest=E2=80=9D the stakeholders could=
 do seemed to be around $11.50 in August 2017, there seemed to be little in=
centive to hold onto BWP shares above that price. And so the stock has=C2=
=A0begun to fall. However, as the stock falls, so too does the 180-average =
price for which Loews can demand tender. This has engendered a real-time ga=
me theory practice known as =E2=80=9Cthe prisoner=E2=80=99s dilemma.=E2=80=
=9D By this logic, the stakeholders assume the worst of their fellow stakeh=
olders and aim to sell first in order to arguably . . . get a better price =
than those who wait. This has created a pile-on where stakeholders are will=
ing to part with their shares below what some might argue is fair value. An=
d no shareholder has the incentive to pay more than this price if Loews has=
 the option to tender below that price level.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Boardwalk=E2=80=99s shareholders =E2=80=94=C2=A0including a=
 hedge fund, Bandera Partners LLC =E2=80=94=C2=A0started complaining (1) th=
at Loews should not be able to exercise the call right and (2) that in any =
case it was manipulating the stock price by=C2=A0<em>talking about </em>exe=
rcising the call right, pushing the stock price down so that when it eventu=
ally exercised the call right it could pay a lower price.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Loews did it anyway. It got the opinion, exercised=
 the call right and paid $12.06 per share; the acquisition closed on July 1=
8, 2018. =E2=80=9CHours after the closing,=E2=80=9D FERC issued a final rul=
e on the treatment of taxes for MLPs that was generally very favorable to M=
LPs, including particularly on the transition for deferred tax liabilities =
(=E2=80=9CADIT=E2=80=9D):</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">FERC =
reiterated that its policy would not=C2=A0automatically permit MLP pipeline=
s to recover an income tax allowance in their cost of service, but MLPs wou=
ld not be precluded from arguing in a rate case that they were entitled to =
an income tax allowance based on an evidentiary record.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Critically, FERC stated that MLPs that were no longer entitled=
 to an income tax allowance could eliminate their overfunded ADIT balances =
without returning the balances to rate payers (whether by refund or amortiz=
ation). ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Final Rule meant there woul=
d be no effect on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s recourse rates.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh well! Turns out everything was fine.=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bandera sued on behalf of Boardwalk shareholders=
,[7] arguing that Loews wasn=E2=80=99t actually allowed to exercise the cal=
l right because nothing bad had happened. The FERC=E2=80=99s new rule does =
not have =E2=80=9Cor will reasonably likely in the future have a material a=
dverse effect on the maximum applicable rate that can be charged to custome=
rs,=E2=80=9D Boardwalk=E2=80=99s rates did not go down, there was no proble=
m.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last Friday Vice Chancellor Travis Laste=
r of the Delaware Chancery Court <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/25737311.268656/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMv=
dXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3IzNnlHNWJ4YkMzVS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBef1=
65ca7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">issued a 194-page opinion</a> agreeing with Bandera. He foun=
d that Boardwalk was not entitled to exercise the call right, and that the =
legal opinion it got from Baker Botts =E2=80=9Cdid not satisfy the Opinion =
Condition because outside counsel did not render it in good faith.=E2=80=9D=
[8] And he found that the present value of Boardwalk=E2=80=99s shares =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0based on management's own projections of future revenue and dis=
tributions =E2=80=94=C2=A0was $17.60, awarding shareholders damages of $5.5=
4 per share or about $690 million total.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.268656/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMTYvanBt=
b3JnYW4tZmlnaHRzLXRlc2xhLW92ZXItd2FycmFudHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTExNzIxX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMT=
E3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3e0424fd" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> talked yesterday</a> about a dispute between JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. a=
nd Tesla Inc. over some warrants. In 2014, JPMorgan bought some warrants fr=
om Tesla. It worried about the risk of Tesla being taken over, which would =
probably be bad for the value of those warrants, so it wrote a takeover pro=
tection into the warrants: If Tesla announced that it was being acquired, J=
PMorgan could adjust the terms of the warrants to preserve fair value. In 2=
018, Elon Musk tweeted that he was going to take Tesla private. He wasn=E2=
=80=99t; it was just a lark that lasted a few weeks and that no one took pa=
rticularly seriously. But JPMorgan adjusted the terms of the warrants anywa=
y, giving itself an extra $160 million of value. JPMorgan=E2=80=99s essenti=
al argument is that the risk it had worried about and protected against cam=
e true, so it got to use the protection it had built for itself. Tesla=E2=
=80=99s essential argument is that the risk came true in a way that did not=
 harm JPMorgan =E2=80=94=C2=A0that actually benefited it =E2=80=94=C2=A0so =
it was just opportunism for JPMorgan to use that protection.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">This is kind of the same case! In 2005, Loews worried abo=
ut MLPs losing their ability to count taxes in their rate determinations. S=
o it wrote a protection into the MLP agreement: If FERC changed the rules a=
bout taxes, Loews could buy Boardwalk back. In 2018, FERC changed the rules=
 about taxes. This worked out fine for Boardwalk, for various specific busi=
ness reasons. But Loews bought Boardwalk back anyway, getting itself an ext=
ra $1.5 billion of value. Loews=E2=80=99s essential argument was that the r=
isk it had worried about=C2=A0and protected against came true, so it got to=
 use the protection it had built for itself. Bandera=E2=80=99s essential ar=
gument was that the risk came true in a way that did not harm Loews =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that actually benefited it =E2=80=94=C2=A0so it was just opportuni=
sm for Loews to use that protection.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
In general this is a hard class of dispute, and I sort of sympathize with t=
he opportunists? If you worry about X, it can be sensible to write a contra=
ct saying =E2=80=9Cif X happens then I get a huge windfall,=E2=80=9D to off=
set the badness of X. And then if X happens and it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>not=
=C2=A0</em>bad, well, sure, that=E2=80=99s a nice windfall for you. Often t=
hat is better and more predictable and easier to administer than having to =
prove after the fact that X was actually bad, and that you suffered and sho=
uld be compensated.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, though, Loe=
ws=C2=A0<em>thought=C2=A0</em>it had written that, but hadn=E2=80=99t quite=
. In fact it did have to prove that what happened was bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
at it was a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0and it=
 couldn=E2=80=99t do that, so it lost.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponso=
