wrote</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One main reason for =
this is that public companies make their statements publicly, to everyone, =
and everyone can buy their stock. If a public company executive says =E2=80=
=9Cwe had a good quarter=E2=80=9D in a magazine interview, people will go b=
uy the stock on the stock exchange; if it turns out she was lying, they wil=
l all have been deceived about a material fact in connection with a securit=
ies trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If a private company executive s=
ays =E2=80=9Cwe had a good quarter=E2=80=9D in a magazine interview, reader=
s might say =E2=80=9Coh interesting, nice to hear good news out of a startu=
p,=E2=80=9D but they will not go buy the stock, because there=E2=80=99s no =
stock for sale and nowhere to buy it. Investors can only buy the stock from=
 the private company itself, in occasional, carefully controlled and lawyer=
ed fundraising rounds. When the company is raising a round, it will put tog=
ether disclosure documents and send them to potential investors, and when i=
t sells stock to those investors it will make them sign a contract saying i=
n effect that they=E2=80=99ve done their due diligence, that they=E2=80=99r=
e only relying on the company=E2=80=99s official disclosure, and that they =
can=E2=80=99t sue the company for lying in a random magazine interview.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The approximate result is that every untrue pu=
blic statement made by a public company has securities-fraud victims, while=
 almost no untrue public statements by private companies have securities-fr=
aud victims.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, to b=
e clear, if you are a private company and you tell investors =E2=80=9Cwe ma=
de $100 million last quarter=E2=80=9D and they invest and you were lying, t=
hat=E2=80=99s still securities fraud, they can sue, the Securities and Exch=
ange Commission can still come after you, there are no exceptions for priva=
te companies. But if you are a private company and you tell a magazine =E2=
=80=9Cwe made $100 million last quarter=E2=80=9D and you are lying, that mi=
ght be fine, as long as you tell the truth to investors before they invest.=
 (Not legal advice!)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This can be awkw=
ard when a private company goes public. Last month Dan Primack <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.268656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYXhpb3MuY29tL2ZpbGluZ3Mtc2hvdy1zd2VldGdyZWVuLWlzbnQtcHJvZml0YWJsZS1kZXNwa=
XRlLWNsYWltcy01MGI0MzE0Yy1lMTMxLTQ0NDYtOTljOS1lNTk1NzBlYWE1MGEuaHRtbA/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBc14e6cd5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">wrote a funny article</a> about Sweet=
green Inc.=E2=80=99s filings for its initial public offering:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Restaurant chain Sweetgreen on Monday filed =
to go public, and revealed that it lost money in each year since 2014.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why it matters: The company lied when it repeat=
edly told reporters it was profitable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a=
 2018 podcast with Recode's Kara Swisher, Sweetgreen co-founder and CEO Jon=
athan Neman replied "We are," when asked if the company was profitable. =E2=
=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company also told the NY Times l=
ast year that its 2019 revenue "topped $300 million," even though it was ac=
tually $274 million.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you li=
e to reporters about being=C2=A0profitable, and then print the truth in you=
r IPO filing, reporters will notice and be mad at you! That is probably the=
 only consequence! They will write articles saying that you lied, which wil=
l hurt your feelings a bit, but whatever. As long as you gave your private =
investors accurate financial statements, and include accurate financial sta=
tements in your IPO filings, you=E2=80=99re fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Still I suppose your lawyers might overthink it a bit and say: Well,=
 the old articles are still out there on the internet, the ones=C2=A0where =
you lied about your financial results. Any rational investor will of course=
 ignore those old articles and look at your IPO filings to see your financi=
al results. But there are a lot of irrational investors in the world, and m=
ore to the point there are a lot of clever securities plaintiffs=E2=80=99 l=
awyers. If you go public and then your stock goes down, someone is going to=
 sue you, saying =E2=80=9Cyou said in a New York Times article that your 20=
19 revenue was over $300 million, but it was really $274 million, and we re=
ad the article and were deceived and bought your stock.=E2=80=9D This is ve=
ry stupid stuff but just to be safe you might as well disclaim those articl=
es now.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so today Sweetgreen <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.268656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0Nzc4MTUvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMzMxNTg5=
L2QxMDQzNjBkczFhLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB284d6320" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">filed an =
amended prospectus</a> for its IPO that includes this paragraph in the risk=
 factors:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Additionally, any pub=
lic statements, including social media posts, from any members of our senio=
r management team or board of directors that are perceived negatively or ot=
her than as intended by the media or our customers could have a material an=
d adverse impact on our brand. For example, in a December 2018 podcast, our=
 Co-Founder and Chief Executive Officer, Jonathan Neman, stated, in respons=
e to a question of whether the company was profitable, that =E2=80=9Cwe are=
.=E2=80=9D As noted in this prospectus, for the fiscal year ended December =
30, 2018, we had a net loss of $31.1 million. Although Mr. Neman was referr=
ing in this response to operating profitability for the third quarter of fi=
scal year 2018 rather than net income profitability under GAAP requirements=
, listeners of the podcast, or readers of subsequent articles that reprinte=
d this statement, including potential investors in our prior private financ=
ings or this offering, may have construed this statement to be referring to=
 GAAP profitability. In addition, in January of 2020, we were quoted in an =
article by the New York Times that revenue for fiscal year 2019 =E2=80=9Cto=
pped $300 million.=E2=80=9D As noted in this prospectus, for the fiscal yea=
r ended December 29, 2019, we had revenue of $274.2 million. Accordingly, t=
his quote did not precisely reflect our revenues for fiscal year 2019. Whil=
e we believe all investors in our private financings since the date of thes=
e public communications had complete and accurate information in which to m=
ake an investment decision, some investors may have given undue reliance on=
 these public communications. Although we would vigorously contest any clai=
m that a violation of the Securities Act occurred as a result of these publ=
ic communications, we cannot assure you that such investors, or regulatory =
authorities, could not make such claims and/or that such sales of securitie=
s around the time of these communications could not subject the company to =
rescission claims. Any such claims could have an adverse effect on the comp=
any. Similarly, potential investors in this offering should not rely on the=
se prior public statements. You should make your investment decision only a=
fter reading this entire prospectus carefully.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That should do it! Of course the problem persists: I=
f you read the old news articles but not the prospectus, then=C2=A0<em>you =
won=E2=80=99t read this risk factor</em>, and you won=E2=80=99t know that S=
weetgreen lied about its 2018 and 2019 results=C2=A0or that it now disclaim=
s those statements. Still, probably good enough.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Note the other point here is that, while Sweetgreen believes (correct=
ly, I think) that those public statements were not securities fraud on=C2=
=A0<em>the private investors who previously bought its stock</em>, because =
they =E2=80=9Chad complete and accurate information in which to make an inv=
estment decision,=E2=80=9D there=E2=80=99s still some risk that those inves=
tors will give it a go and sue claiming that they relied on the inaccurate =
public statements. That seems a bit much to me, but I see why Sweetgreen wo=
uld want to be careful; the frontiers of securities fraud are always expand=
ing.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" =
