</em></span></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[1] The theory is that a p=
artnership is a pass-through entity: It doesn=E2=80=99t pay taxes on income=
, but its income is attributed to its partners, who do (generally) pay taxe=
s. So a pipeline partnership that is owned by some corporations *does* have=
 a tax expense; it=E2=80=99s just that the partners pay the taxes, not the =
partnership.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[2] From last Friday=
=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2573731=
1.268656/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcH=
g_aWQ9MzI2Mzkw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCfc9c418e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Delaware Chancery=
 Court opinion</a>=C2=A0in Bandera Master Fund LP v. Boardwalk Pipeline Par=
tners LP (citations omitted):=C2=A0=E2=80=9CA related component of a pipeli=
ne=E2=80=99s cost of service is ADIT [accumulated deferred income taxes], w=
hich is an accounting concept that arises because various tax provisions au=
thorize pipelines to depreciate their assets on an accelerated basis. When =
calculating recourse rates, however, FERC uses straight-line depreciation. =
Because a pipeline can claim depreciation more quickly for tax purposes tha=
n for rate setting, the pipeline pays lower income taxes in the years when =
accelerated depreciation applies, resulting in greater cash flows than FERC=
=E2=80=99s rate-setting calculations contemplate. Once the period of accele=
rated depreciation ends, the process reverses, and the pipeline ends up pay=
ing higher taxes than FERC=E2=80=99s rate-setting calculations contemplate.=
 By accelerating depreciation and deferring taxes, the pipeline benefits fr=
om the time-value of money. To reflect the fact that the taxes ultimately m=
ust be paid, the pipeline records the accumulated value of the tax deferral=
 on its balance sheet as ADIT. During the years when the pipeline benefits =
from accelerated depreciation and pays lower taxes, the=C2=A0ADIT balance b=
uilds up. After the period of accelerated depreciation, once the pipeline b=
egins paying higher taxes, the ADIT balance declines. In substance, the acc=
elerated depreciation acts as an interest-free loan from the government tha=
t the pipeline eventually must repay. The balance on the pipeline=E2=80=99s=
 balance sheet is therefore referred to as an =E2=80=98ADIT liability.=E2=
=80=99 More importantly for present purposes, FERC historically treated a p=
ositive ADIT balance as a cost-free source of capital. FERC therefore subtr=
acted the ADIT balance from the pipeline=E2=80=99s rate base for purposes o=
f the cost-of-service calculation.=E2=80=9D The question, after FERC=E2=80=
=99s March 2018 announcement of its new policy, was how old ADIT balances w=
ould be treated. The good case for MLPs would be if the ADIT balances just =
went to zero: no taxes, so no deferred tax liability. This would give MLPs =
more room to charge high rates (because they=E2=80=99d no longer have imput=
ed zero-cost financing). The bad case would be if the MLPs had to, e.g., re=
fund ADIT back to ratepayers. The actual result, FERC announced in July, wa=
s the good one for MLPs: ADIT balances would go to zero.=C2=A0</em></p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[3]=C2=A0The chief executive officer of Boardw=
alk, Stanley Horton, =E2=80=9Cinstructed Ben Johnson, Boardwalk=E2=80=99s V=
ice President of Rates and Tariffs, to conduct an expedited analysis of the=
 possible impact on Boardwalk=E2=80=99s three interstate pipelines.=E2=80=
=9D[3] He did, and the impact was mild: Two were =E2=80=9Crelatively protec=
ted=E2=80=9D from any impact, because most of their =E2=80=9Cvolumes were s=
ubject to negotiated rates, meaning that a change in cost-of-service-based =
rates would not affect the pipeline.=E2=80=9D The third =E2=80=9Chad potent=
ial exposure to a rate case, but it too had factors that would help in defe=
nding against any challenge to its rates. Among other things, Texas Gas ser=
ved highly competitive markets, and a majority of its contracts with shippe=
rs provided for negotiated or discounted rates. Assuming a rate case was fi=
led, Johnson estimated that the downside impact of eliminating the income t=
ax allowance would be about $20.5 million. Importantly, Johnson characteriz=
ed his estimate of the downside as a floor, because it =E2=80=98ignores any=
 bounce from rate base increase associated with removal of ADIT.=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D (See note 2 for ADIT.)=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
><em>[4]=C2=A0This and other unattributed quotes in this section are from <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.268656/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzI2Mz=
kw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cDfc9c418e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Chancery Court opinion</a=
>, with citations omitted.=C2=A0The links here are generally to the opinion=
 on the Chancery Court website, but here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.268656/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb=
2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3IzNnlHNWJ4YkMzVS92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cCef165ca7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">a copy of the PDF archived at Bloomberg</a>, just=
 in case.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[5] At one point the opi=
nion quotes Boardwalk=E2=80=99s general counsel, Michael McMahon, making fu=
n of a FERC official for doing this sort of oversimplification: =E2=80=9CDu=
ring a discussion of the March 15 FERC Actions, Jonathon Taylor from the FE=
RC Office of General Counsel ... explained that =E2=80=98when a tax expense=
 decreases, so does the cost of service.=E2=80=99 At the time, McMahon and =
his outside counsel ridiculed that line of reasoning. McMahon wrote to Greg=
ory Junge, a regulatory lawyer: =E2=80=98That was a priceless statement[.] =
[T]axes go down[.] COS goes down[.] This is going to be a train wreck.=E2=
=80=99 Junge responded: =E2=80=98That is . . . just [the] type of 1:1 think=
ing that we were trying to explain is not the case.=E2=80=99 And in its com=
ments to FERC on the NOPR, Boardwalk rejected that simplistic approach. Boa=
rdwalk asserted that it was =E2=80=98misleading=E2=80=99 to equate a change=
 in the cost of service stemming from the removal of the income tax allowan=
ce with a =E2=80=98rate reduction,=E2=80=99 because a cost-of-service chang=
e has =E2=80=98little bearing=E2=80=99 on whether or not a rate reduction w=
ill occur.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[6]=C2=A0Meanw=
hile, Barclays Plc put out a research report saying that Loews =E2=80=9Cwas=
 using a =E2=80=98loophole=E2=80=99=C2=A0in the Partnership Agreement =E2=
=80=98to buy in the assets for what we believe is an extremely attractive p=
rice.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Loews had asked Barclays investment bankers for adv=
ice on exercising the call right, but Barclays equity research and investme=
nt banking were =E2=80=94=C2=A0as they=E2=80=99re supposed to be! =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0managed separately, and the research analysts criticized Loews for do=
ing what its bankers were advising on. Loews got mad: =E2=80=9CLoews=E2=80=
=99 management did not like the report, particularly since Loews had used B=
arclays for advice on the Call Right. Siegel contacted Gary Posternack, Hea=
d of Global M&amp;A at Barclays, to express his =E2=80=98dissatisfaction=E2=
=80=99 with the report. Posternack emailed Jes Staley, Barclay=E2=80=99s th=
en-CEO, with a heads up that he might be =E2=80=98getting a call in the nex=
t day from Jim Tisch at Loews, who is very upset about some equity research=
 commentary that our analyst put out. I should brief you before you speak.=
=E2=80=99 The call ultimately did not take place.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It=E2=80=99=
s a good little story about investment-bank management. In the olden days, =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25737311.268656/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvR2xvYmFsX0FuYWx5c3RfUmVzZWFyY2hfU2V0d=
GxlbWVudHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB83108f74" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">research analysts pum=
ped up stocks</a> in order to win investment banking business; under modern=
 rules, research analysts mostly=C2=A0*lose*=C2=A0investment banking busine=
ss by writing mean things about the companies the bankers are pitching.=C2=
=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[7] The procedural history is =
actually more complicated and interesting than that. What happened is that =
some other shareholders sued to block the call even before Loews exercised =
it. That case was dismissed as not yet ripe, and then the plaintiffs reache=
d a settlement with Loews and Boardwalk that would allow them to exercise t=
he call but require them to do it by a certain date, i.e. before the price =
fell too far. This was done as a class-action settlement that would give Lo=
ews a global release from claims about the call right; the plaintiffs=E2=80=
=99 lawyers told Loews=E2=80=99 lawyers,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CYour clients want to=
 make this purchase. Getting a release on a deal they want to make anyway i=
s actually an amazing outcome for them.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0But when they went to=
 the court to approve the settlement (after the call right was exercised), =
Bandera objected, essentially arguing that the plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers =
had sold out the class=E2=80=99s very good claim in exchange for a fee. The=
 court agreed,=C2=A0rejected the settlement and let Bandera take over the c=
lass action instead.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[8] One side =
note here. The opinion was not =E2=80=9Cin good faith,=E2=80=9D Vice Chance=
llor Laster concluded, but there's something else weird about it. Boardwalk=
 is a limited partnership organized under Delaware law, and the question of=
 whether the new FERC rules would have a =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effect=
=E2=80=9D under the partnership agreement is a subtle question of Delaware =
limited partnership law. But the lawyers at Baker Botts who wrote the opini=
on were not Delaware lawyers. This is actually *common*: Most big U.S. comp=
anies are incorporated in Delaware, virtually all legal issues in U.S. merg=
ers and acquisitions are issues of Delaware law, and most of the lawyers wh=
o advise on those issues are not Delaware lawyers. It=E2=80=99s weird! Last=
er writes: =E2=80=9CA non-Delaware law firm thus rendered a non-explained o=
pinion on the existence of a material adverse effect, a subject on which bo=
th a Delaware law firm (Richards Layton) and a national law firm with a Del=
aware office (Skadden) would not opine.=E2=80=9D And: =E2=80=9CBaker Botts =
is a sophisticated law firm, but it is not a Delaware law firm. Baker=C2=A0=
Botts is also a leader in transactions involving MLPs, but it is not in the=
 habit of opining on complex issues of Delaware limited partnership law. Ma=
ny sophisticated firms render closing opinions on routine issues of Delawar=
e entity law, such as the due formation of an entity or the due authorizati=
on of a contract. Baker Botts generally rendered enforceability opinions un=
der the Delaware Revised Uniform Limited Partnership Act, but the firm did =
not render opinions more broadly on other Delaware issues.=C2=A0In this cas=
e, Baker Botts took on one of the most difficult issues under Delaware law:=
 determining the existence of a material adverse effect. Neither of the Del=
aware firms in this case would render such an opinion.=E2=80=9D Back when I=
 was a lawyer, licensed and practicing in New York but thinking mainly abou=
t Delaware law, I =E2=80=A6=C2=A0found that =E2=80=A6=C2=A0worrying?=C2=A0<=
/em></p>
